          titleEn: 'Mom, There\'s Something I Need to Tell You',
          fullTextEn: 'Mom, I have been carrying these words inside me for a long time. Today I want to let them out.\n\nDo you remember that evening last month? I scored a 72 on my math test and buried the paper at the very bottom of my backpack, terrified to show you. When you asked how I did, the number stumbled out of my mouth in fragments. You went quiet. Those few seconds stretched longer than an entire class. Then you said, simply, "Go fix the ones you got wrong." And that was all.\n\nI thought you had stopped caring. But later that night, on my way to the bathroom, I passed your bedroom door and heard your voice, pressed to a whisper, on the phone with Dad: "I\'m worried sick too — but I don\'t want to crush her with pressure..." There was the faintest tremor in your voice.\n\nMom, I stood outside that door for a very long time. I had mistaken your silence for indifference. Now I understood: it was what remained after you swallowed your criticism, choked down your worry, and chose to leave me something gentler — space.\n\nThere have been so many moments like that one. Whenever I lose my temper and slam my bedroom door, you never chase me in to argue. Instead, a little while later, a cup of warm water appears on the floor outside. When I do well on a test, you smile. When I don\'t, you simply cook one extra dish — the one you know I love. Your love has never been loud. But it has never once been absent.\n\nMom, here is what I want to tell you: thank you for always giving me your patience and keeping the anxiety for yourself. From now on I will work harder — not for the numbers on a test, but so that you will never again have to sit alone in the dark, whispering into a phone, "I\'m worried sick too."\n\nI cannot say these words to your face. So I have written them here, hoping that somehow, you will know.'
