          titleEn: 'Childhood, There\'s Something I Want to Tell You',
          fullTextEn: 'Childhood, I want to say goodbye to you. Not because you were anything less than wonderful — but because I have grown up.\n\nDo you remember that little path to school? Wildflowers spilled from both sides, nameless and abundant, and I was always stopping to squat and count their petals. Five on this one, six on that one... I would count until I was late, my name scratched into the hall monitor\'s notebook. But I never could understand — the flowers were so beautiful. Why on earth couldn\'t I stop to count them?\n\nDo you remember the old banyan tree? Every ten-minute recess, my friends and I scrambled up its trunk like monkeys and sat on the thickest branch, convinced we were the tallest people in the world. A gust of wind would set the leaves rattling — as if the whole tree were clapping for us. You see, happiness was that simple then.\n\nDo you remember that rainy afternoon? I left my umbrella furled on purpose and jumped from puddle to puddle the whole way home. Rain dripped from the tips of my hair to the tip of my nose. I stuck out my tongue and caught a drop — cool, faintly earthy. Mom scolded me the moment I walked in, but I lay in bed that night grinning into my pillow.\n\nNow that path has been widened into a proper road; the wildflowers are gone. The old banyan still stands, but I would never climb it — not because I can\'t, but because the word "childish" has crept into my vocabulary. When it rains, I carry an umbrella without being told — not because I fear getting wet, but because there is an exam tomorrow and I cannot afford a cold.\n\nChildhood, here is what I want to tell you: I know you haven\'t really gone away. You are hiding in those afternoons of counted petals, in the rattle-and-rush of wind through leaves, in the cool, earthy taste of a single raindrop on my tongue. I will keep growing. But I will not forget.\n\nThank you for teaching me this: the most precious things in the world are the landscapes that slip past before you ever think to say goodbye.'
