          titleEn: 'The Roadside Debate',
          fullTextEn: 'In the Spring and Autumn Period, so the story goes, Confucius and his disciples were making their way along a dusty road when two shrill young voices drifted from a village up ahead.\n\nThey found the source under a spreading tree: two boys of seven or eight, cross-legged in the dirt, glaring at each other with the intensity of rival generals. Beside them lay two bamboo baskets, vegetables tumbling out — apparently the argument had trumped the shopping on the walk home from market.\n\n"I have told you eight hundred times!" The boy in blue snatched up a stick and scratched a sun into the earth. "When the sun first rises it is enormous — wide as a carriage canopy. By noon it has shrunk to a plate. Everyone knows things look bigger when they are near. Morning: near. Noon: far. End of discussion!"\n\nThe boy in red snorted. "You use your eyes; I use my skin. Step outside at dawn — chilly, right? Stand under the noon sun — hot as the inside of a steamer. You feel warmer when you\'re close to a fire and cooler when you\'re far away. Even a three-year-old grasps that! Noon: near. Morning: far. Case closed!"\n\n"Seeing is believing!"\n\n"Feeling is truth!"\n\nTheir voices climbed so high they startled every bird from the branches.\n\nConfucius was thoroughly delighted. He motioned his disciples to keep quiet, stepped forward, and said mildly: "Good morning, young sirs. The question you are debating is a genuinely scholarly one. Might I be allowed to think it over as well?"\n\nBoth boys fell silent at the sight of the distinguished stranger, eyes bright with expectation.\n\nConfucius thought. He stroked his beard once, twice, three times — and stroked out not a single answer. At last he shook his head with unfeigned sincerity: "I am embarrassed to admit it, but I truly do not know."\n\nThe boys froze, then exploded into laughter. The one in blue scooped up his spilled greens. "Come on, let\'s go — if even the greatest scholar alive can\'t crack it, this really must be a hard one!"\n\nThe one in red trotted after him. "But I still say I\'m right!"\n\n"I am clearly the right one!"\n\nTheir voices shrank with distance. Confucius watched the two small figures disappear around a bend, then turned to his disciples: "Today I have been taught a lesson. The knowledge between heaven and earth is boundless. To stay humble and dare to say \'I do not know\' — that is the truest wisdom."'
