          titleEn: 'Who\'s Right, Who\'s Wrong',
          fullTextEn: 'Long, long ago, in a small town in the state of Lu, morning sunlight sifted through a veil of cloud and settled on the rooftops.\n\nDown by the creek at the eastern end of town, two boys squatted in the dirt drawing circles with twigs. One was called Shitou — Stone — dark-skinned, loud-voiced, built like a young ox. The other was Douzi — Bean — pale, quick-witted, always two thoughts ahead. They were neighbours, and the town\'s undisputed champion debating team.\n\n"Shitou, look!" Douzi jabbed a finger at the huge red sun hanging above the eastern hills. "The morning sun is enormous — big as the stone mill we use for tofu. By noon it shrinks to the size of a copper coin. Things look bigger when they\'re close, smaller when they\'re far — my mum uses the same principle every time she measures cloth for a new jacket!"\n\nShitou shook his head and fanned himself with an open palm. "You look; I feel. Right now — cool breeze, right? Wait till noon — so hot you\'d want to dive into the creek head-first! Why? Because the sun is closer at noon. Don\'t believe me? Go hug the fire in the kitchen stove — the nearer you get, the hotter it burns. Even a three-year-old knows that!"\n\n"So you\'re saying I\'m wrong?"\n\n"I\'m just saying I\'m more right."\n\nAt that moment a procession appeared on the road from outside town. The elder at its head had a gentle face and eyes that seemed to look a long way into things. Shitou slapped Douzi\'s shoulder. "Look — my grandpa says that\'s Confucius! The most learned man under heaven!"\n\nBoth boys sprinted across the road and planted themselves in the travellers\' path. Douzi spoke first: "Master, is the sun nearer to us in the morning or at noon?" Shitou bobbed his head vigorously: "Yes, yes — whatever you say is final!"\n\nConfucius crouched until his eyes were level with theirs and listened to both arguments with care. He rose slowly, brushed the dust from his robe, and smiled. "Your observations are both sharp, and your reasoning both holds water. But this particular question… I truly do not know the answer."\n\nThe boys stared, then dissolved into laughter. "Even the greatest scholar in the land has things he doesn\'t know?" Confucius nodded without a trace of embarrassment. "Of course. The world holds far more than any single mind can hold. Not knowing is simply not knowing."\n\nShitou scratched his head. "So which of us is right?"\n\nConfucius thought a moment. "Perhaps both of you. Perhaps neither. What matters is this: your willingness to observe, to think, to argue — that is more precious than any answer could be."\n\nHe and his disciples walked on. In the sunlight behind them, two small silhouettes were already deep in a new dispute: "All right then — so where do rainbows come from?"'
