          titleEn: 'The Quarrel at Dawn',
          fullTextEn: 'The sky was barely grey, the rooster still clearing its throat. On the east end of the village stood two households side by side. Little Fish lived on the left, Iron Egg on the right. Both were seven years old.\n\nThat morning Little Fish dragged a wooden stool to the yard gate to watch the sunrise. The sun had just shouldered its way above the mountain ridge — enormous, glowing red, as wide as the great iron pot the village used for festival rice. She sat transfixed, murmuring to no one: "The sun is so big…"\n\n"Of course it is!" Iron Egg materialised beside her, still working his way through half a steamed bun. "The morning sun is big because it\'s close. By noon it wanders off and shrinks."\n\nLittle Fish considered this, then fired back: "If the sun is close in the morning, how come I was shivering when I stepped outside? If it were really near, standing here should feel like squatting next to the stove!"\n\n"That — that\'s because —" Iron Egg\'s words jammed. His bun nearly went down the wrong pipe.\n\n"Because what? Lost for words already?" Little Fish beamed. "Cold at dawn, roasting at noon — obviously the sun is closer at noon!"\n\nIron Egg refused to yield: "My eyes don\'t lie! Big means close!"\n\nLittle Fish stood her ground: "My skin doesn\'t lie either! Hot means close!"\n\nTheir faces had turned the colour of ripe persimmons when a gentleman passing through the village overheard and paused. He wore a long gown slightly faded with travel but kept scrupulously clean, and his eyes brimmed with quiet amusement.\n\n"Well now, quite the spirited discussion," he said, stepping closer. "I come from a long way off, and this question fascinates me as well."\n\nIron Egg and Little Fish each laid out their case. The gentleman listened, then fell into a long silence. At last he crouched to meet the children\'s eyes: "You both argue well. But though I have spent a lifetime reading books, this is one question I cannot answer."\n\n"What?" they cried together.\n\nThe gentleman rose and looked toward the sun, now climbing freely above the ridge. "The world holds more mysteries than any library can contain — even a question as simple as how far the sun stands from us remains unanswered. So never stop asking."\n\nHe walked on, his staff tapping the flagstones. Iron Egg swallowed the last bite of his bun and turned to Little Fish: "Coming to watch the sunrise again tomorrow?"\n\nLittle Fish nodded. "Definitely. Who knows — maybe we can work out the answer on our own."'
