          titleEn: 'Compliment Festival',
          fullTextEn: 'If I could invent one holiday, I would create Compliment Festival.\n\nHave you noticed how much more criticism there is in our lives than praise? Score ninety-eight on a test, and Mum\'s first words are: "Where did those two points go?" Paint a picture, and a classmate announces: "That looks like a pig." Finish fifth in the relay, and Dad shakes his head: "Four people beat you." After enough of this, nobody dares to compliment anyone else — let alone themselves.\n\nSo here it is: Compliment Festival, held every year on the first of June — same day as Children\'s Day. Double the happiness.\n\nThe rule is simple: every person must sincerely compliment at least three others before the day is done. You might praise your deskmate\'s handwriting, tell your mother that her stir-fry is extraordinary, thank the bus driver for the smoothest ride in town, or even commend the street sweeper for polishing the pavement until it gleams like a mirror.\n\nSchools would host a Compliment Competition — not a contest over who receives the most praise, but over who gives the most creative compliment. Imagine someone stepping up to the microphone and saying: "Teacher Li, when you teach, your eyes actually glow — like twin suns — and every desk in this classroom is lit up." The hall would erupt.\n\nThe most daring event is Compliment Yourself. Every participant stands before a mirror and names three of their own strengths out loud. Don\'t laugh — try it. You will discover that praising yourself is far harder than praising anyone else. But once you manage it, a small, surprised voice inside you will whisper: well — I\'m actually not half bad.\n\nI believe that if Compliment Festival truly existed, the world would grow noticeably warmer. Because every sincere compliment is a seed — planted in someone\'s heart, certain to bloom in its own time.'
