          titleEn: 'Silence Festival',
          fullTextEn: 'I want to create a holiday called Silence Festival. You read that correctly: for one entire day, nobody on earth is allowed to open their mouth and speak.\n\nWhy? Because our world is deafening. In class the teacher lectures; at break the corridor erupts; at home the television blares; step outside and car horns pick up the chorus. Dawn to dusk, our ears never rest. I have often wondered: if the whole planet suddenly fell silent for a single day, what would that feel like?\n\nSilence Festival would fall on the second Saturday of May every year.\n\nYou cannot speak, but you may express yourself in every other way imaginable. Write your friend a note on a scrap of paper. Catch your mother\'s eye and smile. Trace a heart on the windowpane with your fingertip. People would discover that mouths are not the only channel of communication — and that some things, written down, carry more weight than they ever did spoken aloud.\n\nIn the classroom the teacher fills the blackboard with chalk while students copy in perfect stillness. Through the open window drift sounds that are normally drowned in the din — a thrush calling from the camphor tree, wind combing through new leaves, the distant clock tower chiming the hour. The world, it turns out, has been speaking all along. We were simply too loud to hear it.\n\nAfter school Mum hands me a folded note: "Made your favourite braised pork today." I turn it over and draw an enormous smiley face on the back. In that moment the scrap of paper feels warmer than any sentence I have ever heard.\n\nWhen Silence Festival ends and people open their mouths for the first time, the words that come out will surely be the important ones — the things they had always wanted to say but never quite managed to speak.\n\nSilence, sometimes, is simply another way of being heard.'
