          titleEn: 'Swap Day',
          fullTextEn: 'I want to establish a holiday called Swap Day. For twenty-four hours, parents and children trade places — children run the household, and parents live under their rules.\n\nWhy? Because my parents do not understand me. They are forever saying, "You kids have it so easy these days," and "We never had luxuries like yours." What they do not know is that homework that never ends, tutoring classes that never let up, and exams that never stop coming are anything but easy.\n\nSwap Day falls on the first day of summer holiday every year.\n\nAt half past six the child marches into the bedroom: "Up! Three test papers are waiting for you!" Dad rubs his eyes and mumbles that he does not want to get out of bed. The child crosses both arms and delivers the classic line: "If you don\'t finish your homework, how will you ever find a job?"\n\nDuring the morning Mum is packed off to two hours of competition-level maths — let her discover what it feels like to understand nothing and be forbidden to leave. At lunch the child inspects her plate: "Put that dish back. Too greasy. Not healthy. Eat more greens."\n\nIn the afternoon Dad sits down to a fifth-grade Chinese paper. Halfway through the essay section he slumps in his chair and announces it is impossible. The child regards him coolly: "Two hundred words and you\'re already whining? The minimum is five hundred."\n\nBy evening the swap is over. The three of us collapse onto the sofa and stare at one another. Dad says: "Your homework is genuinely hard." Mum says: "Two straight hours of class is brutal." I say: "And being a parent is no picnic either — the noodles I cooked for lunch, even I didn\'t want to eat them."\n\nThen we all laughed.\n\nSwap Day is not about exhausting anyone. It is about stepping into the other person\'s shoes and walking a single day\'s road. Understanding, it turns out, sometimes needs nothing more than that.'
