          titleEn: 'The Memory Bakery',
          fullTextEn: 'In 2088 an unremarkable shop appeared on a quiet corner of the city. Its sign bore three words: The Memory Bakery.\n\nThe shop sold one product only — bread baked with a human memory sealed inside. Take a single bite, and you live that memory again.\n\nA boy named Chen Xing was a regular. He never ordered his own memories. Every visit he bought the same loaf: "Grandma\'s Summer." It was the summer he turned five, spent at her countryside house. The moment the bread touched his tongue he was back in that cicada-loud afternoon: Grandma waving a palm-leaf fan and spinning stories, mung-bean soup bubbling on the clay stove, the old yellow dog asleep in the tree shade, one ear twitching at flies. Everything was warm, slow, and sweet.\n\nGrandma had passed away the year before. Chen Xing would never taste her soup again — but inside this shop he could return to that summer as many times as he wished.\n\nOne afternoon a white-haired old man walked in, bought a loaf, took a single bite, and wept. "This is my wedding day," he said. "My wife has been gone three years. I was beginning to forget what her smile looked like. Thank heaven for this place."\n\nThe shop owner was a taciturn, middle-aged man. When customers asked why he had opened the bakery, he gave the same short answer every time: "Because some things should not be forgotten."\n\nThen one day a scientist entered, her expression grave. "Memory bread has a side effect," she said. "The more you consume, the weaker your capacity to create new memories becomes. You will sink deeper and deeper into the past and forget how to live in the present."\n\nChen Xing heard every word. He stood motionless for a long time, the uneaten loaf growing cool in his hands. He thought of Grandma, of the stove, of the soup. Then, very gently, he set the bread back on the counter.\n\n"Thank you," he said to the owner. "I have decided to go and make a bowl of mung-bean soup myself."'
