          titleEn: 'The Last Tree',
          fullTextEn: 'In the year 2120, one tree remained on Earth.\n\nIt stood inside a vast glass dome, watched over by robots around the clock. People travelled from every continent to see it, queuing for three hours or more. A living organism had become the planet\'s most treasured artefact.\n\nTwelve-year-old Lin Xiaoye first encountered it during a holographic-projection lesson. "What is that?" she asked the AI instructor.\n\n"A banyan," the AI replied. "It produces oxygen and once provided shelter for birds and insects. A century ago trees grew everywhere."\n\n"Everywhere?" Xiaoye could not picture it. Her city was built entirely of metal and polymer. The air she breathed was manufactured by purifiers; the food she ate was synthesised from nutrient concentrates. She had never breathed the scent of a flower, never heard wind threading itself through leaves.\n\nThat weekend she persuaded her parents to take her. After four hours in line she finally stood before the dome.\n\nThe banyan was not especially tall. Its leaves had yellowed at the edges; cracks ran through its bark like dry riverbeds. But when a jet of artificial wind passed through the enclosure, the leaves trembled and produced a soft, sibilant sound — sha sha sha. Xiaoye\'s eyes prickled without warning. She could not say why, but the sound made her feel she was remembering something from a very, very long time ago.\n\n"Could you open the dome?" she asked the guard robot. "I want to touch it."\n\n"Contact is prohibited. Human bacteria could accelerate its decline."\n\nXiaoye pressed her palm flat against the glass and stared through the cold barrier at the green leaves quivering in the manufactured breeze. Inside her chest, very quietly, she whispered: I am sorry. We arrived too late.\n\nBack home she made a decision. She would become a botanist and return trees to the earth. Not one — ten thousand, a million.\n\nThat night she dreamed. Wherever she looked there were trees, and wind moved through them, and the air was full of the sound: sha sha sha.'
