          fullTextEn: 'If you could send a letter to your future self, what would you write?\n\nIn 2077, Earth\'s first Time Post Office opened its doors. For the price of one time-coin — roughly one minute shaved from your lifespan — you could mail a letter to any date in the future. It would appear on your doorstep that exact morning, without fail.\n\nEleven-year-old He Ming posted a letter to his thirty-year-old self: "Hey, future me — what do you do for a living? Have you been to the moon? Do you still remember the summer of fifth grade? That was the summer you wished, out loud, to become an astronaut. Did you make it?"\n\nAfter dropping the envelope into the brass slot, He Ming thought about it every day. How would his thirty-year-old self react when that letter arrived?\n\nThe question changed him. From that point on, whenever he was tempted to slack off on homework or quit halfway through a training run, the letter surfaced in his mind. If the man nineteen years from now tore open the envelope and found that nothing — not one thing — had been accomplished, how crushing would that be?\n\nTwo years later he posted a second letter, this time addressed to himself at twenty-five: "I\'m in sixth grade now. My maths has come a long way, and I scored full marks on the fitness test. I am walking toward you."\n\nThe post-office owner was a white-bearded old man. A customer once asked him: "Do these letters really reach the future?"\n\nThe old man smiled. "Whether the letter arrives is beside the point. The moment you set pen to paper, you had already chosen the direction of your future."\n\nHe Ming did become an astronaut. On his thirtieth birthday no letter appeared on his doorstep. But he sat down and wrote one of his own — addressed to the boy he had once been: "Thank you for that letter. Your wish — I made it come true for you."'
