          titleEn: 'The Translation Earbuds',
          fullTextEn: 'In 2065 the year\'s best-selling invention was a pair of earbuds called Omni-Lingua. Slip them in, and you could understand every language on Earth — including the languages of animals.\n\nThe first time fifth-grader Su Xiaomi walked into her garden wearing them, the world cracked open.\n\n"Don\'t step on me! Don\'t step on me!" the grass shrieked beneath her sandals. She leapt sideways, heart pounding.\n\nSparrows bickered overhead: "The wind knocked my nest crooked again." "Want a hand?" "No thanks — your wings are even shorter than mine."\n\nIn the corner a platoon of ants chanted in formation: "Left — right — left! Cookie crumbs sighted at nine o\'clock — all units, move out!"\n\nXiaomi laughed so hard she dropped to her knees. She had never known the garden held this much conversation every single day.\n\nBut gradually different voices surfaced. The old tree in the backyard heaved a sigh: "My roots are sealed under concrete. I can barely draw a breath." A fish in the pond murmured: "The water grows murkier by the week. Three of my neighbours moved away last month." The stray cat curled inside a cardboard box by the gate whispered: "So cold. Nobody fed me again today."\n\nXiaomi stopped laughing. She pulled the earbuds out, and the world fell silent. But she knew — those voices had been there all along. She simply had not been able to hear them.\n\nThe next morning she did three things: chiselled holes in the concrete around the tree\'s roots so they could breathe; spent her pocket money on fish food and scattered it across the pond; built a padded shelter for the stray cat and filled a bowl with kibble.\n\nOmni-Lingua was eventually pulled from shelves — too many owners discovered their pets had been trash-talking them behind their backs, and the resulting disputes overwhelmed the courts. Xiaomi did not mind. She had already learned to hear those voices without the earbuds. All you need to do is crouch down and truly look at the world.'
