          titleEn: 'The Time Camera',
          fullTextEn: 'In a dusty corner of the attic I found a camera unlike any I had seen. Its casing was tarnished copper; beside the lens sat a small dial engraved with two arrows — one marked "Past," the other "Future."\n\nI turned the dial to "Past" and pressed the shutter, aiming through the window. The print slid out: the same view, yet utterly different. The trees stood taller, greener; the sky stretched a deeper blue; a knot of children in old-fashioned uniforms played elastic-skip on the field below. In tiny type along the bottom: April 12, 2005.\n\nTwenty years ago — this exact spot.\n\nHeart hammering, I swung the dial to "Future" and fired again. The print that emerged stopped my breath. The trees had vanished. In their place rose a wall of grey high-rises. The sky was a murky, sulphurous yellow. No children on the field — only a few masked adults hurrying past, heads down. Along the bottom: April 12, 2045.\n\nI refused to believe it. I shot frame after frame, and every print came back the same. The future was grey.\n\nI set the camera down and ran — downstairs, out the door, across the schoolyard. The sky was not as blue as it had been twenty years ago, but the trees still stood, birds still called, classmates still bounced a basketball against warm concrete. I drew a long breath. The air still carried the scent of grass.\n\n"There is still time," I said to myself.\n\nI put the camera away and told no one. But from that day I began to conserve water, sort my rubbish, and leave nothing on my plate. When classmates asked why I had changed so suddenly, I would smile and say: "Because I have seen the future."\n\nEvery today is the past of some future. The choices we make now are tomorrow\'s photograph.'
