          titleEn: 'Unforgettable Primary School Life',
          fullTextEn: 'The last winter of sixth grade, the blackboard at the back of the classroom got a new heading: "Goodbye, My Primary School."\n\nI stood before it, chalk in hand, and went blank. Six years of living — too much, too tangled to know which thread to pull first.\n\nIn the end I wrote a single sentence: "Thank you for that rainstorm in third grade."\n\nIt was autumn of third grade. A downpour without warning. After the bell only Xiao Yu and I remained in the classroom — neither of us owned an umbrella. We waited the better part of an hour; the rain did not relent. Xiao Yu dug through his bag and produced a crumpled plastic bag. "What if… we used this?"\n\nWe ripped the bag open, lashed it to our heads with backpack straps, and charged. We fell twice. Our shoes became buckets; our trousers became mud paintings. But we laughed the entire way. At the entrance to our neighborhood he said something I have carried for three years: "From now on, when it rains, we run together. Two people getting rained on get less wet than one."\n\nThat makes no sense whatsoever. And yet, strangely, I have always believed it.\n\nOver the next three years Xiao Yu and I were inseparable. We teamed up for the science fair (blew up a lightbulb, still placed third), stood in the hallway together as punishment (for passing notes in math about weekend plans), and swore an oath under the banyan tree by the field: "Same middle school. No exceptions."\n\nNow I stood at the board again, and Xiao Yu walked over, read what I had written, and smiled. "You still remember?"\n\n"Of course."\n\nHe said nothing else. He picked up a second piece of chalk and beside my sentence drew a lopsided umbrella and two stick figures running through the rain.\n\nThe setting sun happened to slant through the window just then, and gilded the chalk drawing in gold.\n\nUnforgettable primary school life — you do not need to fill an entire blackboard. One rainstorm. One person. Enough.'
