          titleEn: 'Unforgettable Primary School Life',
          fullTextEn: 'The afternoon they took the graduation photo, I sat alone in the hollow classroom and found it — a line scratched into the corner of my desk: "Zhang Xiaomin was here. September 1, 2019."\n\nI had carved it in secret on my very first day. At seven I thought it was daring. At twelve I think it is childish. But I crouched down, read those crooked little characters again, and shook my head, smiling.\n\nSix years. They happened right here, at this desk.\n\nI remember first grade, when I could not hold a pencil properly no matter how I tried. The teacher wrapped her hand around mine and, stroke by stroke, wrote a single character: 人 — "person." "First learn to be human," she said, "then learn to write." I did not understand. Now I do.\n\nI remember third grade, when my deskmate and I went to war over an eraser — so furious I refused lunch. That afternoon he slid a bag of crackers across the desk: "Hungry?" I forgave him on the spot. The eraser disappeared who knows where, but I can still taste those crackers. Seaweed flavor.\n\nI remember the relay at the fifth-grade sports day. I ran the anchor leg. The baton nearly slipped during the handoff; the whole class held its breath. I hurled myself forward. When I broke the tape my knee was torn open and bleeding, but roaring in my ears was the loudest cheer I have ever heard.\n\nThe door swung open. Our homeroom teacher stepped in, surveyed the empty seats, and said, "Still here?"\n\n"One more minute." I stood, took a last look at the carved corner of the desk.\n\nSix years of primary school taught me many things — writing, arithmetic, running, friendship. But the most important lesson was this: some things feel unremarkable while you have them. Only after they are gone do you learn their name: youth.'
