          titleEn: 'Unforgettable Primary School Life',
          fullTextEn: 'On graduation day I pulled open my desk drawer and found a diary I had forgotten existed. The first page, in wobbling handwriting, read: Sept 1 Sunny Today is the first day of school My teacher is pretty My deskmate is a boy He has freckles on his nose\n\nI laughed out loud. The characters were ugly, the punctuation non-existent, but the page felt as fresh as though it had been written that morning in 2018.\n\nI flipped further.\n\nThird grade: Today I got chosen as group leader! Mum says she\'ll buy me ice cream to celebrate!\n\nFourth grade: I came third in the class on finals but I\'m not that happy because my goal was first. Teacher said: progress matters more than ranking. I think she\'s right.\n\nFifth grade: Had a fight with Xiao Li today. I think she was being unreasonable. But lying in bed tonight I think maybe I was the one who grabbed her paintbrush first. I should apologise tomorrow.\n\nThe last page was blank. At the top it said "Sixth grade." Below — nothing. Too busy, probably. Forgot to write.\n\nI picked up a pen and filled in the final entry:\n\nJune 30 Sunny Today is the graduation ceremony I wore my new dress Stood in the schoolyard and sang the farewell song Halfway through the teacher started crying I didn\'t cry But after I walked out through the school gate I cried in secret Because I suddenly realised I have walked through this gate for six years After today I will never walk back through it as a student\n\nI closed the diary, drew a smiley face on the cover, and slid it into my bag.\n\nSome things you are certain you will forget. But open a single page, and all the winds come rushing back.'
