          titleEn: 'My Hometown in the Future',
          fullTextEn: 'One morning twenty years from now, I wake and push the window open. The sky over Zhaotong is blue — the blue of silk that has just been washed.\n\nWhen I was small, a ditch ran past our front door, foul and black, breeding mosquitoes so thick in summer they could lift a person off the ground. That ditch is now a clear stream. Weeping willows and osmanthus trees line the banks; old men practice tai chi in the dappled shade while children squat at the water\'s edge watching fish — yes, there are fish now, and shrimp, and frogs.\n\nGetting to Kunming used to mean seven or eight hours on a bus, the mountain road all hairpin turns, passengers dizzy by the second hour. Now a direct high-speed rail covers it in two. More remarkable still is the town\'s "sky bus" — a quiet, solar-powered shuttle that crosses from east end to west in three minutes. Grandma no longer has to walk half an hour to market.\n\nThe greatest change is the school. My old classroom had windows that let in the wind; in winter we stamped our feet to keep warm. The new classrooms have smart climate control, holographic blackboards, and every child has an AI study companion. But what moves me most is this: on the playground, children are still jumping elastic bands, and from the classrooms you can still hear the bright chorus of reading aloud. The technology has changed. The sound of children laughing has not.\n\nAt dusk I stand on the new observation deck and gaze at the rolling Wumeng range. The setting sun paints the peaks gold — exactly as it did twenty years ago.\n\nHometown, my hometown. You have changed so much, and yet somehow nothing has changed at all. What changed are the roads, the bridges, the buildings. What remains are the mountains, the water, and the smiles on the faces of people walking home under the evening sky.\n\nThis is the future hometown I dream of: technology that makes life easier, without a single degree less of human warmth.'
