          titleEn: 'My Hometown in the Future',
          fullTextEn: '"Welcome home!" The smart lock on the front gate recognized my face and greeted me — in the Yunnan dialect, warm and broad.\n\nFifteen years since I left. I was the first college graduate the village ever produced. Now I am an urban planner, and I have come back for the new-town design forum.\n\nWalking down the street, I could barely trust my eyes. The mud I remembered was asphalt now, flanked by rows of ginkgos — one gust of autumn wind and the ground turned gold. More astonishing still, each tree wore a small "air-purification orb," a recent environmental technology that converts exhaust directly into oxygen.\n\nThe farmland had changed too. Where Grandpa once bent double transplanting rice under a merciless sun, drones now crisscrossed the paddies — sowing, fertilizing, pest-controlling. Grandpa sat on the field bank sipping tea, watching the drones and shaking his head: "That thing is far more capable than I ever was."\n\nBut the deepest change was in the people. The young used to flee — "no future in the village," they said. Now many had returned: one ran a heritage guesthouse, another sold local specialties online, a third volunteered at the village library. On the square at dusk, the evening dancers outnumbered any city park.\n\nAt the design forum the village chief unrolled a map and said: "We want to keep that old paddy and the ancient tea garden on the hill. The new town can grow — but roots cannot be severed."\n\nI looked at that map and felt warmth flooding through me. This — this is the future hometown I wanted: not demolishing the past to start over, but growing new shoots from old roots.'
