          titleEn: 'My Hometown in the Future',
          fullTextEn: 'An email arrived: "Dear Student Li — Congratulations. Your hometown has been awarded the 2045 National \'Most Beautiful Hometown\' Grand Prize. Please return this Saturday for the ceremony."\n\nMy hometown? Won an award? I rubbed my eyes to make sure I was not dreaming.\n\nThe maglev train delivered me in two hours. Stepping off, I froze. The station was a building sheathed in living green — roof thick with grasses and wildflowers, so that from a distance it looked like a small hill. My cousin picked me up in a car manufactured entirely from recycled plastics, grinning the whole drive: "Our town has the highest waste-recycling rate in the country!"\n\nThe biggest transformation was the river. The ditch I used to sprint past with my nose pinched now rippled blue-green, pebbles visible on the bottom. Coffee shops and bookstores lined both banks, and young people sat by the water writing code and sketching illustrations — they no longer needed the big cities, because here the internet was just as fast and the air a thousand times cleaner.\n\nThe ceremony was held in the town square. The trophy was not metal; it was pressed from local clay and rice straw. The inscription read: "This town spent twenty years proving that development need not devour the land, and that home need not be a place to escape."\n\nI held that rough, earth-colored trophy and felt tears rising — not for the prize itself, but because I was finally looking at a hometown I did not need to flee.\n\nA future hometown does not need to become another metropolis. It only needs to become — a place people want to come back to.'
