          titleEn: 'The Moment I Was Understood',
          fullTextEn: 'I had always believed my father did not understand me.\n\nHe is a soldier. His sentences have always sounded like orders: "Up at seven!" "Finish your homework today!" "Men don\'t cry!" In his world everything seemed to have a regulation answer, and my feelings were never part of the equation.\n\nIn fifth grade I fell in love with drawing. Textbook margins, the backs of exam papers, even the tablecloth — everything became my canvas. Dad saw my doodles, frowned, and said: "What\'s the use of drawing? Put your energy into studying."\n\nI did not argue. But from that day on I only drew late at night, after making sure he was asleep. Sketchbook after sketchbook, hidden under my bed.\n\nBefore sixth-grade graduation, the school held a student art exhibition. The art teacher said my work could be displayed. I was thrilled and terrified in equal measure — thrilled that my painting had been recognized, terrified that Dad would find out.\n\nThe day of the exhibition, I told him nothing.\n\nBut as I stood before my painting, a familiar silhouette appeared in the gallery doorway — Dad. He wore his crisp military uniform, unmistakable in the crowd. My heart hammered. I had no idea what he would say.\n\nHe walked to my painting and stood there for a long time. It showed a small boy sitting at a window gazing at stars, the sky outside a deep, deep blue. The title read: "Waiting for Dad to Come Home."\n\nDad looked at the painting, then turned to me. His lips moved as if to speak, but in the end he said only four words: "You drew this well."\n\nThat was the moment.\n\nThose four words were not heavy, yet they struck an enormous echo inside me. I knew he had understood the painting — a child\'s loneliness and longing while a soldier-father was away. He was never incapable of understanding me. He simply never knew how to show it.\n\nThe moment of being understood is not about how many words the other person says. It is about the instant when, at last — they see you.'
