          titleEn: 'The Moment I Surpassed Myself',
          fullTextEn: 'Every pair of eyes in the class was on me. I stood before the pull-up bar, palms drenched in sweat.\n\nPhysical education exam. Pull-ups. A perfect score required six. My personal best was — zero. That is correct: I could not complete a single one.\n\nI had been heavy since I was small. My classmates called me "Panda." At first I found the nickname endearing, but by fifth grade, when everyone else could swing onto the bar with ease, "Panda" started to mean "clumsy."\n\nThe PE teacher looked at me and said: "How about you do push-ups instead?" The words were well-intentioned. But the feeling of thirty-nine pairs of eyes turning to stare was like a bucket of ice water dumped over my head.\n\nI refused the substitution. I spent three months — every morning at six on the field, three laps first, then dead hangs. In the beginning I could only hold on for ten seconds before dropping, arms so sore I could barely grip my chopsticks at dinner. After a month I could hang for twenty seconds. After two months I hauled myself up for the first time — ugly as a fish dangling from a hook.\n\nExam day. I walked to the bar. Drew one deep breath. Jumped and gripped. One. Two — my arms howled, but I clenched my teeth. Three. Four — the class began counting aloud. On the fifth my hand nearly slipped. "One more!" someone shouted — I never found out who.\n\nSix.\n\nMy chin barely cleared the bar — and in that moment I heard cheering. But louder than the cheering was the voice inside me: "I did it."\n\nWhen I dropped down my legs were trembling. The PE teacher walked over, patted my shoulder, and said: "Full marks."\n\nSurpassing yourself in that moment is not about becoming a different person. It is about finally proving that you are far stronger than the person you thought you were.'
