          titleEn: 'The Moment of Forgiveness',
          fullTextEn: 'Xiao Lin and I did not speak for an entire semester.\n\nThe cause was almost laughable. After the midterm exam, the teacher noticed that two students sitting front and back had identical scores, and suspected cheating. Because I sat in front, the suspicion of copying fell on Xiao Lin.\n\n"I didn\'t copy from you!" she told me, eyes red. But the whole class was already whispering, as if the verdict had been passed.\n\nAnd I — I chose silence. I did not speak up for her.\n\nBecause, honestly, being considered "the source of the answers" made me feel a tiny bit... proud.\n\nXiao Lin stopped talking to me after that. She switched seats, ate lunch separately, even took a different route to and from school. At first I didn\'t care. But as the days stretched on, the empty chair beside me grew more and more like a hole — a hole that kept reminding me: you did something wrong.\n\nOn the last day of the semester, I found a slip of paper in my desk. Xiao Lin\'s handwriting: "Actually, I stopped being angry a long time ago. I was just waiting for you to speak first."\n\nI clutched the note and ran out of the classroom, finding her at the end of the corridor. She had her back to me, packing her bag.\n\n"I\'m sorry." The words came out much quieter than I had imagined.\n\nShe turned around and looked at me. Said nothing. Just smiled once.\n\nIn that moment, the stone that had been lodged in my chest for half a year shattered.\n\nThe moment of forgiveness was not only about her forgiving me — it was about me finally having the courage to face my own mistake. What she had been waiting for was not the two words "I\'m sorry," but the moment I admitted that silence, too, is a kind of wrong.'
