          titleEn: 'The Moment I Grew Up',
          fullTextEn: 'I never knew when a person counted as "grown up." Until that afternoon.\n\nI came home from school and called out "Mom, I\'m back" as usual when I pushed the door open. No one answered. In the living room I found her curled on the sofa, face drained of color.\n\n"Mom? What\'s wrong?"\n\n"Nothing. Just a headache. I\'ll lie down a bit." Her voice was barely there.\n\nBefore, when she said "nothing," I believed her. This time I noticed the ultrasound printout on the coffee table and a few pills scattered beside it. I picked up the report — I could not read most of it, but the words "further examination recommended" sent my heart racing.\n\nI did not press her. Instead —\n\nI went to the kitchen and poured a glass of warm water, brought it to her. Then I found the pill bottle, read the instructions, checked whether she had taken the right amount. I opened the fridge, washed whatever vegetables I could find, and followed a phone tutorial to make the simplest thing I knew: tomato egg-drop soup and fried rice. The taste was probably mediocre, but when I set the tray in front of Mom, she froze.\n\n"You made this?" She sat up. Her eyes were a little red.\n\n"Mm. Eat first." My voice was calm when I said it, but inside I was panicking — I had no idea what was actually wrong with her. I only knew that right now she needed someone to look after her.\n\nThat evening Dad came home from his business trip. I showed him the ultrasound printout. After reading it he said one thing to me: "Thank you."\n\nI knew those two words were not tossed off casually. They meant he no longer saw me as a child.\n\nThe moment you grow up is not when your height suddenly shoots up. It is when you discover that the person who has always taken care of you needs you to take care of her too.'
