          titleEn: 'The Guide on My Path of Chasing Light',
          fullTextEn: 'If my six years of primary school were a road, then Teacher Zhou is the person who lit a lamp at the darkest bend.\n\nBefore fourth grade I was the most "transparent" student in class. Average grades, introverted, no extracurriculars — like a pothos plant in the classroom corner: alive, but noticed by no one.\n\nFourth grade brought a new homeroom teacher: Teacher Zhou. Her first assignment was for every student to write a self-introduction. I wrote three lines: "My name is xxx. I like reading. I don\'t really like talking." Three lines. Everyone else filled half a page.\n\nThe next day Teacher Zhou called me to her office. I assumed a scolding was coming. Instead she said: "Your writing may be short, but every word is true. I like real people."\n\nThen she gave me a task: recommend a book at each weekly class meeting. Two minutes would be enough.\n\nThe first time I stood at the podium my voice was barely louder than a mosquito. But Teacher Zhou, sitting in the very last row, gave me a thumbs-up. The second week was a little better. The third week... By the end of the semester I was standing at the podium speaking fluently for five minutes.\n\nIn fifth grade she recommended me for the school\'s "Young Reader" showcase. I went. In sixth grade she signed me up for the citywide reading-sharing competition. I won second prize.\n\nAt the graduation ceremony I spoke on behalf of the entire class. Sitting in the audience was the fourth-grade child who could only write a three-line self-introduction — unrecognizable now.\n\nAfterward, Teacher Zhou walked over and said: "You\'re glowing."\n\nI looked at her and suddenly understood: on the path of chasing light, not everyone can find the light alone. Some people need a guide — someone who opens a window for them and lets the sunlight stream in.\n\nTeacher Zhou was the person who opened my window.'
