          titleEn: 'That Time, I Chose Honesty',
          fullTextEn: 'It was a unit quiz in fourth grade.\n\nThe paper landed on my desk and the very first question stumped me. I stole a glance at my deskmate\'s sheet — the answer was right there, clear as day. The classroom was silent; the teacher sat at the front, head down, grading homework. Nobody was watching.\n\nMy heart hammered. Copy or not? One flick of my eyeball, two extra points.\n\nThe tip of my pen hovered in midair. I hesitated for a few seconds. Then — I pulled my gaze back, lowered my head, and wrote an answer I had come up with on my own. I was not sure it was right.\n\nAfter handing in the paper, I discovered my palms were drenched in sweat. Those few seconds of hesitation had been more exhausting than the entire exam.\n\nThe next day the papers came back. My answer was wrong. My deskmate\'s was right. If I had copied, I would have scored 92. Without copying, I scored 90.\n\nTwo points. For one instant, I regretted it.\n\nBut only for an instant. Because I quickly realized: if I had copied, the 92 on that paper would not have been entirely mine. Every time I looked at the score, I would remember that two of those points were stolen. But the 90 I held now — every single point was spotlessly clean.\n\nI did not tell anyone about it when I got home. Not because 90 was embarrassing, but because I felt this was something that belonged only to me.\n\nThat time, I chose honesty. The choosing took only a few seconds, but it taught me a truth I will carry for life: scores can be made up on the next exam. Honesty, once lost, has no retake.'
