          titleEn: 'That Time, I Gathered Courage',
          fullTextEn: 'The class talent show was approaching, and they needed someone to sing a solo.\n\nNo one raised a hand. The silence was suffocating. Our homeroom teacher\'s gaze swept from face to face like a searchlight.\n\nUnder the desk, my hand clenched into a fist. I wanted to volunteer. I desperately wanted to.\n\nBut I did not dare.\n\nBecause in fourth grade I had sung in front of the entire class, forgotten the lyrics halfway through, and someone laughed. The laughter was not malicious, but it took up residence in my brain for two years and refused to leave. After that, I never sang in front of anyone again.\n\n"Nobody?" the teacher asked a second time.\n\nOne second before she was about to assign someone, my hand went up.\n\nI could hardly believe what had happened. It was as if a "brave me" had snatched control from a "scared me" and raised the hand before I could react.\n\nFor the next two weeks I practiced every day until my throat went raw. I sang on the balcony, sang to the mirror, even sang to the neighbor\'s cat (it listened and then walked away — apparently not a fan).\n\nThe day of the show, I stood on stage. The lights were blinding; the audience a dark mass. I could feel my knees trembling faintly.\n\nThe music started. During the eight-beat intro I had eight thoughts — seven of them were "can I still run?"\n\nThen I opened my mouth. The instant the voice left my body, all the fear vanished. The melody carried me. I heard my own voice — imperfect, a little shaky, but steady.\n\nThe last note faded. Two seconds of silence. Then applause.\n\nThat time, I gathered courage. Not because I was no longer afraid, but because even while I was afraid, I still chose to stand up there.\n\nSome roads you can only understand by walking them yourself — and beneath your feet there was never the cliff you had imagined.'
