          titleEn: 'A Different Kind of Classroom in Life',
          fullTextEn: 'The clamor of the wet market rose and fell around me, the air a tangle of fish-stink and the clean scent of greens. The summer I turned ten, Mom sent me to buy groceries alone for the first time. That "market class" is one I have never forgotten.\n\nShe pressed fifty yuan into my hand along with a shopping list: two jin of tomatoes, a box of eggs, one block of tofu. "Pick them yourself. And don\'t let anyone cheat you." She was laughing as she pushed me out the door. I pocketed the money, excited and uneasy in equal measure.\n\nAt the first stall I stopped. "How much for tomatoes?" "Three-fifty a jin." I chose a few, placed them on the scale — "Two jin and a touch over, seven seventy." I hesitated, then remembered Mom saying I could bargain. "Could you make it seven even?" The vendor sized me up and grinned: "Little negotiator, aren\'t you? All right, seven."\n\nSecretly pleased, I moved on. At the egg stall I learned to hold each one against the light and check for cracks. At the tofu stall I discovered the difference between silken and firm. By the time I had worked my way around, every item on the list was accounted for, with six yuan in change.\n\nBack home, Mom inspected my haul and nodded — but pointed to one tomato: "There is a soft spot on the underside. Next time, flip them over and look." That single remark taught me something larger: in everything you do, look carefully. Never trust the surface alone.\n\nOver the rest of that summer I returned to the market several more times, graduating from tight-lipped nervousness to easy banter with the vendors. The wet market, that different kind of classroom, taught me how to communicate, how to count carefully, and above all how to stand on my own feet. There is knowledge in every corner of life — for those with eyes willing to look.'
