          fullTextEn: 'Who says classrooms only exist in schools? Grandma\'s kitchen is the warmest classroom I have ever attended.\n\nLast Spring Festival the whole family went home for the holiday. On New Year\'s Eve, Grandma tied on her apron and said: "This year\'s reunion dinner — you are going to help me cook a dish." I rolled up my sleeves, electric with excitement. She had chosen to teach me her specialty: sour-cabbage fish.\n\n"Fillet at an angle, following the grain." She guided my hand on the knife, but my slices came out thick and thin, as if something had gnawed on them. Grandma showed no impatience. She took the knife back, demonstrated once, and said, "Slowly. You cannot rush hot tofu."\n\nMarinating the fillets, she taught me to add salt, cooking wine, and egg white, then toss gently with my fingers. "Too hard and the flesh breaks apart. Too soft and the flavor won\'t penetrate. Cooking is like being human — you must know the right measure." I memorized her words, cradling the fish as if it were something precious.\n\nWhen the sour cabbage hit the hot oil it crackled and spat, and the whole kitchen filled with a fragrance that pulled everyone in. Grandma let me control the flame. "High heat to reduce, low heat to simmer. Knowing when to blaze and when to ease off — that comes with experience."\n\nThe finished dish arrived at the table with slices of uneven size, but the family ate every last piece. Dad gave a thumbs-up. Grandma smiled until every wrinkle on her face smoothed out.\n\nWhat Grandma\'s kitchen taught me extends far beyond one recipe. Patience, measure, timing — these principles carry into schoolwork and into life with equal force. This classroom has no blackboard and no desks, yet it gave me a kind of wisdom no textbook ever could.'
