          titleEn: 'A Different Kind of Classroom in Life',
          fullTextEn: 'There are classrooms in school buildings, and there are classrooms in cornfields. The autumn I spent harvesting corn with Grandpa was the most exhausting and most worthwhile lesson I have ever attended.\n\nDuring the National Day holiday I went back to the family farm. Grandpa said the corn was ready and asked whether I wanted to help. I agreed instantly, thinking it was nothing more than a bit of hand work.\n\nAt half past five the next morning, the sky barely gray, Grandpa was already sharpening his sickle in the yard. I followed him into the field, bleary-eyed, and discovered that the cornstalks towered over me. Their leaf edges were sharp as little knives; I had barely pushed through before my arms wore a lattice of red scratches.\n\nGrandpa taught me the technique: one hand grips the ear, the other steadies the stalk — snap downward, twist. It looked simple. But my ears came off trailing husks and stalk; several broke in half. Grandpa\'s rough, powerful hands did not miss once. By midmorning he had filled two large baskets. My basket barely had a layer at the bottom.\n\nThe sun climbed. Sweat soaked through my shirt; my palms raised raw blisters. For the first time I understood that "sweat dripping onto the soil beneath the grain" is not a poem. It is a taste. Grandpa handed me a water bottle and said quietly, "Tired? This is the weight of food."\n\nWe did not stop until two in the afternoon. On the walk home my arms throbbed, but looking at the cart heaped with golden corn, I felt a groundedness I cannot name.\n\nThis field classroom had no textbook and no teacher\'s desk, yet it taught me what labor truly costs and what food truly weighs. Whenever I see corn on the dinner table now, I think of that sweat-drenched autumn, and of Grandpa\'s hands — rough, yet so deft.'
