          titleEn: 'A Different Kind of Classroom in Life',
          fullTextEn: 'I never imagined that getting lost would become a lesson I carry for life.\n\nIn the summer after fifth grade, the school organized a hike through Kunming\'s Xishan Forest Park. Halfway up, a squirrel caught my eye. I followed it without thinking, and by the time I looked up, the trees had closed around me. My classmates\' voices were gone.\n\nMy heart shot to my throat. No phone signal. Trees in every direction, all alike, stone steps leading nowhere familiar. Fear climbed me like a vine, and tears blurred the edges of my vision.\n\n"Don\'t panic. Think first." I forced myself to breathe deeply. Our teacher had said: if you are lost, stay put or find a landmark. I scanned my surroundings and spotted a sign not far away — "Nie Er Pavilion → 300 m." That was our meeting point.\n\nI followed the arrow, checking trail markers as I went. Every few minutes I looked back to memorize the path behind me, so I could retreat if I had gone wrong. After what felt like an hour — probably twenty minutes — the upturned eaves of the pavilion appeared through the leaves, and with them, the sound of my teacher calling my name.\n\n"Where did you go?!" She was half-furious, half-frightened. I told her everything, face burning. She held a stern expression for a few seconds, then reached over and patted my shoulder: "But your response was right. Calming down and finding markers — that matters."\n\nThose twenty minutes in the forest were the longest class I have ever sat through. They taught me this: when you are lost — in a wood or in a life — panic solves nothing. Stillness and method are the keys out. Since that day, whenever an exam makes me anxious or a problem seems unsolvable, I think of the version of myself who stood among the trees on Xishan, drew one deep breath, and began to look for signs.'
