          titleEn: 'That Bowl of Ginger Soup',
          fullTextEn: 'The winter I was in third grade, I was caught in a downpour and came down with a high fever. That night, the bowl of ginger soup Grandma carried to my bed became the warmest memory of my childhood.\n\nSchool let out that afternoon under a sky that had gone suddenly dark. Clouds hung overhead like an upturned iron pot, and rain crashed down without warning. I had no umbrella. I ran. Five minutes of road, and every stitch of clothing was soaked through, my shoes full of water. By the time I stumbled inside I was shaking head to toe, my skull thick and heavy.\n\nOne look at me and Grandma\'s hands flew. She pressed the back of her palm to my forehead — "Burning up!" She bundled me into dry clothes and a quilt, then turned and disappeared into the kitchen.\n\nHuddled under the covers, I heard the rhythmic thud of a knife on the cutting board and the clink of bowls. Minutes later Grandma reappeared carrying a steaming bowl. The soup was amber, studded with red dates and wolfberries, the sharp heat of ginger blooming through the room.\n\n"Drink it while it is hot. Sweat the fever out." She handed me the bowl and sat on the edge of the bed, watching. I took one sip and my tongue caught fire, but a current of warmth slid down my throat and into my stomach. Grandma laughed: "Good medicine is bitter, they say."\n\nI drank it in small, careful mouthfuls. Warmth spread through me like a slow tide. At some point I fell asleep under her gaze. When I woke the next morning, the fever had broken and my head was clear. I turned and saw Grandma slumped over the bedside chair, neck bent at an angle that must have ached. She had been there all night.\n\nThe taste of that ginger soup — spicy with a hidden sweetness, sweet with a hidden warmth. Now that I am older, every rainy day brings back that winter night, and Grandma walking in with the bowl in her hands. It was never just soup. It was medicine simmered from love.'
