          titleEn: 'My First Bike Ride',
          fullTextEn: 'Among my childhood memories, one gleams like a medal of honor — the day I learned to ride a bicycle.\n\nFor my tenth birthday Dad gave me a blue bike. I wheeled it to the open ground in our compound, certain I could simply climb on and go, the way people did on television.\n\nThe bike moved two meters before the handlebars twisted and I toppled into a flower bed, bike and all. My knee was scraped raw, my palms stinging. Dad hauled me up, barely concealing a grin: "Riding is about balance. Sit steady, pedal slow."\n\nOn the second attempt, Dad held the seat from behind. I gripped the handlebars so hard my knuckles went white, palms slick with sweat. "Look ahead. Don\'t look down." His voice came from just behind me. I tried to relax. One revolution. Two. The bike began to glide forward, smooth and straight.\n\n"Dad, hold on tight!" I shouted as I rode. No answer. I glanced over my shoulder — and there he stood, ten meters back, hands on hips, beaming.\n\nHe had let go without a word.\n\nIn that instant the bike wobbled. But this time I did not fall. Instinct took over; I corrected the steering and steadied myself. And in that moment I understood the secret of riding: believe you can keep your balance, and you truly can.\n\nThat evening I circled the compound again and again, the wind cool on my face, so happy I wanted to shout. This small event taught me something I have carried ever since: many things we assume we cannot do are already half-accomplished the moment we are brave enough to begin.'
