          titleEn: 'My Grandma',
          fullTextEn: 'My grandmother is sixty-seven this year. Her silver hair is always combed without a strand out of place, and her wrinkled hands are rough yet strong. In my heart, Grandma is the most stubborn person on earth.\n\nHer stubbornness begins in the vegetable garden. The family has plenty to eat; Mom and Dad long ago urged her to stop growing vegetables. She will not hear of it. Before dawn every morning she shoulders her hoe and heads out. "Homegrown vegetables are the only ones you can trust — who knows how many pesticides are on the market ones?" She has said this hundreds of times. Nobody can change her mind.\n\nLast autumn it rained for a solid week and the garden flooded. Dad said forget it, try again next year. Without a word Grandma pulled on her rubber boots and marched into the field. She straightened the fallen cabbages one by one, bound them to bamboo stakes, then dug a drainage channel to draw off the standing water. She worked in the rain the entire afternoon. When she came home she was soaked through, mud caked to her knees.\n\nI handed her a towel, aching: "Grandma, was it worth it?" She wiped the rain from her face and smiled. "A vegetable is a living thing — ignore it, and it dies. People are the same. Once you have started something, do not abandon it halfway."\n\nHer stubbornness extends to my studies. Every evening while I do homework she sits beside me, stitching shoe soles. She cannot read most of the questions, but she says: "If I sit here, you will not slack off." Once I tried to sneak a look at my phone. She saw through it instantly: "When you finish, you can play. Do one thing at a time."\n\nGrandma\'s stubbornness is the kind that makes you angry and heartbroken at once. But when you think about it, every ounce of her stubbornness is earnestness toward life and love toward her family. I love my grandmother — I love her fierce refusal to settle for less.'
