          titleEn: 'My Deskmate',
          fullTextEn: 'My deskmate is called Xiao Lin. He is not tall. His round eyes always look as if they are laughing. He has one extraordinary talent: no matter how bleak the situation, he can conjure laughter out of thin air. We all call him "the Pistachio."\n\nOnce, after a math exam, the class average was barely in the sixties. Everyone\'s face looked like a frost-bitten eggplant. After the teacher left, silence hung in the room like fog. Xiao Lin suddenly stood, shaped his hand into a microphone, adopted a newsreader\'s tone, and announced: "Breaking news: the entire class has been hit by a mathematical cold front. The lowest score has dropped to — " he paused dramatically — "a figure classified as state secret. Apologies for the inconvenience." The class erupted.\n\nBut do not think Xiao Lin is only a comedian. One event changed my view of him entirely.\n\nAt the fifth-grade sports day he signed up for the eight hundred meters. Frankly, with his build, nobody gave him a chance. Sure enough, by the second lap he had fallen to dead last. Someone shouted: "Just quit, come off the track!" He shook his head, clenched his teeth, and kept running. Over the final half-lap he moved slower than a walk, face crimson, every step like treading on cotton.\n\nWhen he crossed the finish line he was last. He doubled over, gasping, then looked up and grinned at us: "Last place… but I finished the whole course." Nobody laughed. The applause started on its own.\n\nThat is my deskmate Xiao Lin — someone who manufactures joy in the valleys and refuses to surrender on the hills. He taught me this: optimism is not ignoring difficulty. It is smiling while you face it.'
