          titleEn: 'I Give a Thumbs-Up to the Sanitation Worker',
          fullTextEn: 'She doesn\'t have a name in my life—just "the auntie with the broom." But she deserves the biggest thumbs-up I can give.\n\nEvery winter morning at 5 AM, when the city is still sleeping, I hear her: the rhythmic scratch of a broom on pavement. Through my bedroom window, I can see her under the streetlight—breath visible in the cold, hands red, moving steadily.\n\nOne rainy summer evening, a storm drain blocked. Garbage, leaves, and muddy water pooled in the intersection. People wrinkled their noses and walked around. She rolled up her pants, waded in, and cleared the drain with her bare hands.\n\nPassersby covered their noses and took detours. She didn\'t even flinch.\n\nBefore she was done, the road was clean. After, you\'d never know there had been a flood. That\'s her superpower: making messes invisible.\n\nI give her a thumbs-up for her perseverance—rain, shine, or snow, she shows up. I give her a thumbs-up for her dignity—doing work that others look down on, without ever looking down on herself. I give her a thumbs-up for her quiet impact—because every clean street is her masterpiece.\n\nOrdinary work done with extraordinary heart. That\'s worth all the thumbs-ups in the world.'
