          titleEn: 'I Give a Thumbs-Up to Mom',
          fullTextEn: 'If I could give anyone in the world a thumbs-up, it would be Mom. Not for anything heroic—for the way she treats a bowl of rice.\n\nMom cooks dinner every night. She could make it simple—steam rice, stir-fry one dish, done. But she never does. She plans meals. She balances nutrition. She makes sure there\'s always something green, something with protein, something I like.\n\nI once said: "Mom, just order takeout."\n\nShe said: "Eating carelessly and eating carefully are different. What goes into your stomach matters."\n\nThen came the burst pipe incident. One Sunday, the kitchen pipe exploded. Water everywhere. I panicked. Dad panicked. Mom looked at the flood, turned off the main valve, grabbed towels, and started mopping. Calm as a math teacher solving a problem.\n\nDad said: "Should we call a plumber?"\n\n"Give me twenty minutes," Mom said. She watched a YouTube tutorial, got tools from the closet, and fixed it. Fixed. The. Pipe.\n\nDad and I stared. "Easier than grading thirty compositions," she shrugged.\n\nI thumbs-up Mom for her daily care—because treating every meal seriously is treating life seriously. I thumbs-up Mom for her calm strength—because when everything falls apart, she holds it together. I thumbs-up Mom for being Mom—because she makes the ordinary feel extraordinary.'
