          titleEn: 'I Give a Thumbs-Up to Grandpa',
          fullTextEn: 'My grandpa is seventy-three years old, and he\'s learning to use a smartphone. I\'m giving him the biggest thumbs-up of my life.\n\nIt started during COVID. We were isolated in different cities. Grandpa couldn\'t visit. Phone calls weren\'t enough. He decided to learn video calling.\n\n"Teach me that... screen thing," he told Mom.\n\nThe learning process was comedy gold. Day 1: he couldn\'t find the camera app. Day 3: his first selfie showed only his forehead. Day 7: he successfully video-called us—but held the phone upside down, so we saw the ceiling.\n\n"I can see the ceiling fan but not you, Grandpa," I said.\n\n"Oh!" He flipped it. His face appeared, grinning like a child who\'d solved a puzzle. "I did it!"\n\nHe was as happy as a child—no, happier.\n\nOver the next months, he learned WeChat, emoji (he sends me the same thumbs-up emoji twelve times per message), and even short videos. His first video: a shaky pan of his garden with the caption "My tomatoes."\n\nWhen I asked why he tried so hard, he said: "Being slow is okay. Being afraid to start—that\'s not okay."\n\nI thumbs-up Grandpa for his courage to learn something completely new at seventy-three. Age isn\'t a reason to stop. Fear is. And Grandpa chose curiosity over fear.'
