          titleEn: 'I Give a Thumbs-Up to Myself',
          fullTextEn: 'This might sound arrogant: I\'m giving a thumbs-up to myself.\n\nNot for being the smartest or the most talented. But for being the person who trembled on stage—and didn\'t walk off.\n\nOur school speech competition. I was chosen. I didn\'t choose to be chosen.\n\nThe photo that captured the moment: me, standing at the podium, gripping the microphone stand so hard my knuckles turned white. The teacher later framed it for the class wall.\n\nWhat the photo doesn\'t show: the three seconds before I spoke. Three seconds that felt like three centuries. In those three seconds, I thought about running. About faking sick. About the emergency exit.\n\nBut I opened my mouth. And words came out.\n\nThey came slowly at first. Shaky. Like a baby deer\'s first steps. But by the second minute, something shifted. I forgot the audience. I forgot the microphone. I just... talked.\n\nI placed second. Not first. But the certificate isn\'t the point.\n\nThe point is: there\'s a photo on the class wall of a girl gripping a microphone stand with white knuckles. She was terrified. She did it anyway.\n\nI thumbs-up her. I thumbs-up the trembling but persistent her. Because courage isn\'t the absence of shaking—it\'s moving forward with shaking hands.'
