          titleEn: 'Stealing Bayberries',
          fullTextEn: 'Whenever I think of my most unforgettable childhood memory, I always come back to the "heroic feat" of stealing bayberries from Grandma\'s tree with my cousin.\n\nThat summer I was seven, staying at Grandma\'s house. In her courtyard stood a bayberry tree, and every June its branches hung heavy with purple-red fruit like agate beads. Grandma said the berries weren\'t fully ripe yet — we should wait a few more days. But to a seven-year-old, "a few more days" felt longer than a year.\n\nOne afternoon, Grandma went down for her nap. My younger cousin and I exchanged a glance, and without a word we tiptoed to the bayberry tree. It wasn\'t very tall — the lowest branch was just within reach if I stood on my toes. I dragged over a small stool, climbed up, and plucked one berry, popping it straight into my mouth.\n\n"How is it?" my cousin asked eagerly. I wrinkled my face — sour! So sour my eyes squeezed shut. But after the sourness faded, a thread of sweetness appeared. "Delicious!" I mumbled, my lips already stained purple with juice.\n\nWe ate faster and faster. My cousin was shorter and couldn\'t reach the bigger ones up high, so I picked them for him. We ate and laughed, one for you, one for me, and before we knew it we\'d gone through a whole handful. Our shirt fronts were splattered with purple-red juice, our fingers dyed solid purple — we looked like two little monsters fresh from a dye vat.\n\n"You two!" Grandma appeared behind us out of nowhere. We froze, mouths still bulging with one last bayberry we didn\'t dare chew. Grandma looked at us, then looked at the picked-bare branches, and said with a straight face: "Fine, eat. But when your teeth go numb, don\'t come crying to me."\n\nThat evening, our teeth were indeed wrecked — we couldn\'t even bite through tofu. Grandma brought warm water for us to rinse our mouths, muttering: "That\'s what you get for being greedy." But as she turned away, I clearly saw her hiding a smile.\n\nThat bayberry tree grew old over the years and barely bears fruit anymore. But every season when bayberries appear in the markets, I think of that sweet-and-sour afternoon.'
