          titleEn: 'My First Train Ride',
          fullTextEn: 'That year I was eight, and I took the train to Dali for the first time to visit my aunt. The journey played like a movie — one that still replays in my memory.\n\nOn departure day, Mom brought me to Kunming Railway Station. It was far bigger than I had imagined — crowds surging, announcements echoing from every direction. I gripped Mom\'s hand tightly, terrified of getting lost. After our tickets were checked and we entered the platform, I saw a green train up close for the first time — longer than it ever looked on television, car after car stretching to the vanishing point.\n\nOn board, I claimed the window seat. The instant the train moved, my whole body was glued to the glass. The city flew backward — tall buildings became fields, fields became hills. Tunnels came one after another; each time the window went suddenly black I let out a little "ah," then cheered when sunlight burst back in.\n\nMom sat beside me reading, amused by my constant exclamations. Across from us sat a white-haired old man. He pointed out the window: "Young one, does that mountain look like an elephant to you?" I pressed my forehead to the glass and studied it — it really did! We began competing to see who could spot more animal-shaped mountains in the passing landscape.\n\nThe train reached Dali at dusk. The moment I stepped off, a fresh breeze rushed over me, carrying a fragrance I couldn\'t name. In the distance, Cangshan Mountain wore the evening glow like a giant dressed in purple, standing in quiet majesty.\n\nThat train journey taught me something: the world is vast, and the scenery outside the window is always richer than you imagine. Those moments with my face pressed against the glass were the purest joy of my childhood.'
