          titleEn: 'Poking the Hornets\' Nest',
          fullTextEn: 'Childhood bravery is sometimes just recklessness. The summer I was eight and poked a hornets\' nest — that memory still sends a chill down my spine.\n\nThat summer, a hornets\' nest appeared under the eaves of Grandpa\'s house. Gray, round, bigger than a fist. Grandpa said he would get someone to deal with it. But my neighbor Dabao and I figured we could handle it ourselves.\n\nWhile the adults were away, we dug out Grandpa\'s long bamboo pole. Dabao would do the poking; I would provide "backup." He raised the pole and crept closer, his hands shaking so badly that the tip kept wobbling. "Just poke it already!" I urged from behind. Dabao gritted his teeth and jabbed hard —\n\nThe nest fell. And with it came a dark, buzzing army.\n\n"Run!" I screamed, spinning around. Dabao dropped the pole and sprinted after me. The hornets caught up — one stung my neck, another got Dabao\'s ear. We howled, stumbling and crashing through the kitchen door, slamming it behind us.\n\nGrandpa came running. Seeing the welts swelling on my neck and Dabao\'s ear, he was caught between fury and laughter. He dabbed ointment on us while lecturing: "Hornets\' nests are toys now? Don\'t show off about things you don\'t understand!"\n\nThe welt on my neck took three days to go down. Every time I touched that spot, I could still feel the buzzing vibration of the hornets in the air. That experience taught me a lesson I never forgot: bravery is not recklessness — ask an adult before messing with things you don\'t understand.\n\nLooking back now, that gray hornets\' nest and two dirt-smeared kids make for the most comical page in my childhood.'
