          titleEn: 'My Future Self',
          fullTextEn: 'Twenty years from now, on a certain morning, the alarm rings three times before I finally crawl out of bed. Outside the window, Kunming\'s sky is as blue as ever. Sunlight falls on my white coat draped over the chair.\n\nYes — my future self is a pediatrician.\n\nWalking into the hospital, I hear a child crying in the corridor. A little boy clings to his mother\'s leg, refusing to enter the examination room, his face smeared with tears and snot. I crouch down and pull a lollipop from my pocket — a habit I developed after becoming a doctor. My pockets always have candy.\n\n"Hey there — can you guess what flavor this lollipop is?" He peers at me with tear-blurred eyes. "Strawberry?" "You got it! But first you have to let me look at your throat. After that, it\'s all yours." He hesitates, then opens his mouth.\n\nAfter the examination, I write the diagnosis and medication on the chart. His mother asks if he needs an injection. I shake my head with a smile: "Medicine will do — he\'ll be fine in three days." The boy, lollipop in mouth, finally breaks into a grin.\n\nIn the afternoon there is a minor surgery. Suited up, I stand under the shadowless lamp, scalpel in hand. The little girl who sat at her desk memorizing texts a dozen years ago could never have imagined herself standing at an operating table. But my hand is steady — steadiness earned through countless hours of practice.\n\nThe surgery goes well. Walking out of the operating room, the child\'s parents thank me again and again. The feeling is like getting a hundred on a test and being praised by the teacher — simple, pure satisfaction.\n\nAfter work, I drive past my old school. It\'s still there, only the trees by the gate have grown taller. I roll down the window and hear children reading aloud inside. Twenty years ago, my voice was among those sounds.\n\nFuture self, remember this: you became a doctor not to wear the white coat, but to help more children grow up healthy. Keep going, future me.'
