          titleEn: 'My Future Self',
          fullTextEn: 'I am thirty years old, standing in a bright classroom with chalk dust settling on my fingertips. On the blackboard are four characters: "Early Departure from Baidi City." Below the podium, thirty-two pairs of eyes shine up at me.\n\nYes — I became a primary school Chinese teacher. Just like Teacher Li, who once taught me.\n\n"Students, Li Bai set off by boat from Baidi City and reached Jiangling in a single day. Do you know how fast that is?" I draw the Yangtze River on the blackboard. "It\'s about the distance from Kunming to Dali, but he traveled by water — gibbons calling from both banks, peaks flashing past. How do you think Li Bai was feeling?"\n\nA girl with a ponytail raises her hand: "Really happy! Because he just got released!" The whole class laughs. So do I — she\'s right. Li Bai had just been pardoned; of course he was overjoyed.\n\n"Exactly — that\'s why he wrote \'a thousand li to Jiangling, returned in a single day.\' When you\'re happy, doesn\'t time feel especially fast?" The students nod vigorously.\n\nAfter class, the girl runs up to me: "Teacher, could I write poems like Li Bai someday?" I crouch down to her level: "Of course you can. Start observing life right now, write down what you see, and you\'ll be a future Li Bai."\n\nHer eyes light up for an instant, and she runs off. Watching her bounce away, I think of myself at her age — the same age, the same kind of Chinese class, the first time I fell in love with words.\n\nMy future self stands at a three-foot podium, doing exactly what Teacher Li once did: planting a seed in a child\'s heart. The seed is small, but it will grow.'
