          fullTextEn: 'Shoelace. I looked down at my shoelace. There I was, standing on the podium, the principal holding up the certificate, hundreds of eyes fixed on me from below — and the only thought in my head was: my shoelace is loose.\n\nIt all started a month earlier. The school held a "Campus Reader" recitation contest, and my Chinese teacher signed me up. For a solid month I practiced in front of the mirror every single day, reciting Zhu Ziqing\'s "Haste" no fewer than two hundred times. Mom said I even mumbled "The swallows have gone, and they will come again" in my sleep.\n\nI cleared the preliminary round and the semifinal. On the day of the finals, I was so nervous that I could only eat half a steamed bun for breakfast. In the waiting area, I listened to the contestants before me — some with beautifully rounded voices, others brimming with emotion — and my heart kept sinking.\n\nWhen my turn came, I took a deep breath and walked onstage. The spotlight hit me straight on; the audience blurred into a haze. I gripped the microphone, and my voice trembled on the very first line. But as I kept reading, I stopped looking at the crowd. All I thought about was how Zhu Ziqing must have felt when he wrote this piece, how time slips through our fingers. By the last sentence my voice had steadied.\n\nApplause. Louder than I expected.\n\nThen came the awards ceremony. When the principal announced "First prize —" followed by my name, I froze for a full two seconds. The classmate beside me gave me a shove: "It\'s you! Go up!"\n\nI walked onto the podium. The principal smiled and handed me the certificate. At that very instant I glanced down — my shoelace was loose. A white lace dangling against the red carpet, looking thoroughly ridiculous. I nearly burst out laughing.\n\nBut in that moment I suddenly understood something: perfection doesn\'t matter. I was standing right here — shoelace undone, heart pounding, palms sweating — and this was the most real version of me. And the most real version of yourself deserves any podium there is.'
