          titleEn: 'A Silhouette in the Rain',
          fullTextEn: 'The rain came down hard that day. Standing under the eaves at the school gate, I saw a silhouette I will never forget.\n\nThe dismissal bell had just finished ringing when the sky went dark. Raindrops hammered the ground, splashing up white spray. Most classmates had already been picked up by their parents. I called Dad, and he said he was on his way.\n\nAfter twenty minutes of waiting, I finally spotted a familiar figure running toward me through the curtain of rain. It was Dad. He carried only a small folding umbrella, and his clothes were already more than half soaked. By the time he reached me he was panting, hair plastered to his forehead, rainwater streaming down his cheeks.\n\n"Let\'s go," he said, raising the umbrella over my head. It was small — barely enough for one person. We walked side by side, and I looked up: Dad had tilted the umbrella entirely toward me. His right shoulder was completely exposed to the rain.\n\n"Dad, hold it over yourself too." I pushed the umbrella toward him. He pushed it back: "I\'m fine — thick skin, won\'t melt."\n\nI didn\'t push again. I looked at his profile — a few strands of white hair at his temples. When had those appeared? The wrinkles at the corners of his eyes looked deeper in the rain. He took long strides, walking on the outer side to block the splashing water so I wouldn\'t have to.\n\nWhen we got home, Dad\'s entire right side was soaked through, while his left side was perfectly dry — the dividing line ran exactly along the umbrella\'s edge. He took off his jacket and went to the bathroom to towel his hair, as if nothing had happened.\n\nThat half-dry, half-wet silhouette is the most unforgettable moment of my growing up. Dad doesn\'t know how to say love, but that umbrella — always tilted toward me — is his way of saying I love you.'
