          titleEn: 'Crossing the Finish Line',
          fullTextEn: 'Legs heavy as lead, lungs on fire, the finish line ahead shimmering into a band of white light. That was the instant I crossed the line in the 800-meter race — and the most unforgettable moment of my life so far.\n\nI was never a runner. In PE class, I always finished the 800 meters dead last. But for the fifth-grade sports meet the class was short on participants, and the PE delegate signed me up whether I liked it or not.\n\nThe starting gun fired and I sprinted with everything I had. The first lap went all right — I hung with the middle of the pack. But halfway through the second lap I began falling behind. My legs grew heavier with every stride, my breathing turned ragged, and a taste of rust settled in the back of my throat.\n\nFor the final half-lap I was practically walking. The runners ahead had pulled so far away I couldn\'t read their numbers. Only one other slow boy remained beside me. We glanced at each other, said nothing, and kept shuffling forward.\n\nThen I heard them — my classmates, yelling from the stands. "Go! Go!" "Run!" "You\'re almost there!" Their voices rolled toward me like a tidal wave. I have no idea where the strength came from, but my legs opened up and I was running again.\n\nThe finish line: ten meters — five — three —\n\nThe instant I crossed it, everything went silent. The cheering, the shouting — all of it vanished. The entire world went quiet for one second. Then sound came flooding back like a dam had burst. I doubled over, palms on my knees, gasping huge mouthfuls of air.\n\nThat moment taught me something: a finish line isn\'t long — just a few centimeters — but crossing it and not crossing it are two entirely different things. So much in life works the same way: at the very moment you most want to quit, push on a few more steps, and you win.'
