          titleEn: 'My First Speech Failure',
          fullTextEn: 'The day of the fourth-grade class committee election, I experienced my first public failure. That event left a deeper impression on me than any success ever has.\n\nI was running for class president. I had spent a whole week preparing, memorizing my speech until I could recite it in my sleep. But the moment I stood at the lectern, facing more than forty pairs of eyes, my mind went completely blank.\n\n"Hello everyone, I am running for…" And then I froze. Mouth open, not a single word coming out. First there was silence below. Then someone giggled. My face burned as if it were on fire, my palms slick with sweat. The teacher beside me encouraged me gently: "Take your time. Continue when you remember."\n\nHead lowered, I forced myself to think. I finally recalled the next line, but my voice came out no louder than a mosquito\'s whine. I stumbled and stuttered my way through the rest, then practically fled back to my seat. In the final vote, I received four ballots — one of which I had cast for myself.\n\nOn the walk home I kept my head down the entire way. Mom came to pick me up. Seeing my reddened eyes, she didn\'t press. At home she poured me a glass of milk and said softly: "Embarrassed?" I nodded. "Did you remember it?" I nodded again. "Good. Next time, before you step up there, say it a hundred times in front of the mirror."\n\nI did not become class president that year, but the experience taught me one thing: failure is not frightening. What is frightening is not daring to face it. When the election came around again in fifth grade, I practiced in front of the mirror for two solid weeks. This time, I did not forget a single word.'
