          titleEn: 'Being Wrongly Accused',
          fullTextEn: 'One day in third grade, I was wrongly accused by a teacher. That "unable to defend myself" feeling still stings whenever I think of it.\n\nIt was art class. Xiao Jie, who sat next to me, accidentally spilled ink on my drawing paper. I was just about to wipe it up when the art teacher walked over. She saw the ink on my hands and on the paper and assumed I had been making a mess.\n\n"Why are you playing with ink? Can\'t you paint properly?" She scolded me in front of the whole class. My face burned: "It wasn\'t me who spilled it — it was Xiao Jie —" Before I could finish, she cut me off: "Stop making excuses."\n\nXiao Jie sat right there, head down, silent. He could have explained for me. But he said nothing.\n\nI was made to stand for the rest of the period. Standing beside the lectern, with the eyes of forty-some classmates on me, I wanted to disappear. Tears circled in my eyes, but I forced them back — I would not let anyone see me cry.\n\nAfter class, Xiao Jie came up to me and said quietly: "I\'m sorry. I was afraid of getting scolded too, so I didn\'t dare speak up." I looked at him and couldn\'t find any words. In that moment I realized that something hurt more than being scolded by the teacher: a friend\'s silence when you needed him most.\n\nThis incident left a deep impression not because of the injustice, but because it taught me two things. First: you must have the courage to admit your own mistakes. Second: when someone else is wrongly accused, you must be brave enough to stand up and tell the truth.'
