          titleEn: 'It Snowed',
          fullTextEn: 'It almost never snows in Kunming. So when real snow actually fell one winter, the whole school went wild.\n\nIt happened during third period that morning. Something white began drifting past the windows. At first everyone thought it was bits of paper, but then someone shouted: "It\'s snowing!" The classroom erupted. The teacher called for quiet three times to no effect, and finally she couldn\'t help laughing either: "Fine — go look for five minutes."\n\nThe entire class charged out the door. So did every other class — every classroom was like a beehive with its lid popped off, students swarming into the open. The playground filled instantly, screams and laughter rising and falling in waves.\n\nThe snowflakes were small, melting the moment they touched your palm. I tilted my head back and opened my mouth, wanting to catch one and taste it. Cool, and absolutely flavorless. Yet the sheer sensation of the sky sprinkling something down on us was inexplicably thrilling.\n\nThe ground quickly grew damp, but nothing stuck. Classmates grabbed the chalk box from the teacher\'s desk and used it as a "snow basin," scraping what little accumulation they could find from the grass at the edge of the field. After a long struggle they managed to pack a single snowball the size of a walnut. Everyone passed it around like a treasure, until it finally melted into a puddle in someone\'s palm.\n\nThe five minutes were long past, and the snow had stopped. Everyone drifted reluctantly back to the classroom. Someone patted the snowflakes clinging to their school uniform into a textbook to keep as a "bookmark."\n\nThat snowfall lasted perhaps fifteen minutes and left no trace on the ground. But it left a mark in every one of our memories. For the rest of that day, there was only one topic in the entire school: "It snowed!" For the children of Kunming, those fifteen minutes were more precious than the whole winter.'
