          titleEn: 'A Day During Chinese New Year in 2100',
          fullTextEn: 'New Year\'s Eve, 2100. Seven in the morning. The smart home assistant "Xiao Tuan" woke me with a piece of bronze-bell music. "Good morning. Today is New Year\'s Eve. Temperature: twelve degrees. Kunming: sunny. Your parents have departed from the lunar base and are expected home by ten."\n\nYes, by 2100 humanity had built a base on the Moon. Mom and Dad are lunar agriculture researchers, growing low-gravity vegetables up there. Ordinarily they can only reach me through holographic video — their images on screen are three-dimensional and lifelike, but you cannot touch them.\n\nAt ten o\'clock sharp, a silver shuttle landed on the neighborhood\'s aerial parking platform. The hatch opened and Mom and Dad stepped out. I ran up and threw my arms around Mom — three months since we had last seen each other, and she had lost a little weight. "Everything on the Moon is fine. I just missed you so much." She ruffled my hair.\n\nDinner was prepared by Xiao Tuan and me together. It handled precise temperature and seasoning; I was in charge of plating and setting off firecrackers — although in 2100 firecrackers are the holographic-projection kind, with sound and light effects identical to the real thing but producing no smoke or noise.\n\nAt the table, Dad had brought back vegetables grown on the Moon. They were twice the size of Earth\'s, but tasted about the same. Grandpa took a bite and said: "Moon-grown vegetables? Nothing special. Your grandma\'s cured meat is still better." The whole family burst out laughing.\n\nAfter dinner we put on VR glasses to watch the Spring Festival Gala. The 2100 Gala has an "immersive mode" — you can stand center stage while the singers circle around you. Grandma found it too dizzying. She said the old-fashioned television was better.\n\nDuring the midnight vigil, holographic fireworks bloomed across the night sky outside the window, their rainbow light playing on every face. Dad held his tea, Mom leaned back on the sofa, and Grandpa and Grandma dozed beside them.\n\nIn 2100 the vehicles have changed, the firecrackers have changed, the Gala has changed. But the moment the whole family sits together, I realize — the taste of reunion has not changed in a hundred years.'
