          titleEn: 'A Day During Chinese New Year in 2100',
          fullTextEn: 'New Year\'s Day, 2100. At the stroke of midnight, chimes rang out, synchronized by satellite across the globe. I stood on the rooftop terrace of my home in Tengchong, watching holographic fireworks bloom above the volcanic range. A dragon-shaped light formation spiraled over Gaoligong Mountain; its tail swept across the hot springs of Rehai, sending up plumes of colored mist.\n\n"Happy New Year!" Seven time zones\' worth of voices came through my earpiece — my AI study-group classmates from China, Japan, Brazil, and France. We attend virtual class together every week. Chinese New Year is a Chinese holiday, but by 2100 it has become a global cultural festival.\n\nOn the morning of New Year\'s Day, following Tengchong tradition, Mom and I went to Heshun Ancient Town. The flagstone paths looked the same as a hundred years ago, but along the streets a few patrol robots had been added, dressed in red "New Year outfits," clasping their hands and bowing to every passerby: "Gongxi facai!"\n\nWalking down Dashi Lane, I caught a familiar scent — rice noodles. A century-old shop was still making them by hand, only the stove had been replaced with a solar-powered heater. The owner, an eighty-year-old man, said the shop had been running since his great-grandfather\'s generation. "Machine-made ones aren\'t tasty. Only handmade ones have soul."\n\nIn the afternoon, the whole family went to Beihai Wetland. By 2100, the wetland had tripled in size — environmental protection had done its work, and many species of birds that had disappeared had returned. I saw a purple swamphen with my own eyes; its feathers were blue-purple, gleaming in the sunlight. Grandma said she had seen one as a child too, but then they vanished for decades.\n\nThat evening at home, I projected the day\'s holographic photos onto the living room wall. The ancient town, the rice noodles, the purple swamphen, the red-dressed robots — the 2100 New Year had the novelty of the future and the flavor of the past.\n\nIn my diary I wrote one sentence: "The best thing about Tengchong in 2100 is not the flying cars or the AI robots — it is that bowl of rice noodles whose taste has not changed in a hundred years."'
