          titleEn: 'A Day During Chinese New Year in 2100',
          fullTextEn: 'New Year\'s Eve, 2100. I was writing the character for "Spring."\n\nExcept I was not writing on paper. I was using a light pen, writing in mid-air. Golden strokes hovered before the door frame, glinting softly. Each stroke drifted slightly with the wind, as if alive.\n\n"It\'s crooked — that horizontal is too long." Grandma directed from the sidelines. She was ninety-six, but in excellent health — medical technology in 2100 had pushed the average lifespan to one hundred and ten. Grandma insisted that every year the Spring couplets be handwritten. "Store-bought ones are ugly, and printed ones have no soul."\n\nI adjusted my strokes and finally produced a pair that satisfied her. First line: Science advances a thousand miles a day. Second line: Family love endures ten thousand springs. Horizontal scroll: The joy of family. Grandma read them over once and nodded approvingly: "Not bad. You\'ve improved."\n\nAt noon the whole family started wrapping dumplings. Of course 2100 has dumpling-making robots, but our family never uses them. Mom rolled the wrappers, Dad mixed the filling, and Grandma and I did the wrapping. My dumplings came out lopsided; Grandma\'s were fast and beautiful. She teased me: "Ten years of practice and you still wrap like this."\n\n"My talent is writing light-pen couplets, not wrapping dumplings," I protested. Everyone burst out laughing.\n\nWhen we ate, one dumpling turned out to have a coin inside — an old tradition Grandma had kept alive. Dad bit into it and lit up like a little kid. Grandma said: "Coins have been antiques for a long time in 2100, but whoever finds one will have good luck in the new year."\n\nOutside the window, a drone fleet arranged itself into a golden dragon across the night sky. Inside, the four of us sat around the table eating dumplings and watching the light show through the glass. Grandma used the light pen to write a 福 character in the air, then pasted it upside-down on the door.\n\n"Upside-down means \'fortune has arrived,\'" she said. This custom had been passed down from her own grandmother, more than a hundred years running. Some things cannot be made obsolete by time.'
