          titleEn: 'A Day During Chinese New Year in 2100',
          fullTextEn: 'On the second day of the New Year in 2100, Dad and I "went back" to the old family home.\n\nI say "went back," but that is not quite right. The real old home — Grandpa\'s village — had vanished in the wave of urbanization fifty years earlier. What we used was a "Temporal Holographic System," a technology that can perfectly reconstruct historical scenes.\n\nI put on the holographic glasses and our living room disappeared. In its place stood a small courtyard of gray brick and dark tile, red couplets pasted on the gate. This was the old home as it looked around 2030 — how it appeared when Dad was five and celebrated New Year there. The data came from videos and photographs Grandpa had saved before he passed away; AI had rebuilt them into a three-dimensional space.\n\n"Look, this is our kitchen." Dad\'s voice was thick with emotion. A young woman was busy at the stove — that was Grandma as a young woman. Though it was only a holographic image and you couldn\'t see into her eyes, the way she bent forward in her apron was exactly like the grandma in my memory.\n\nIn the courtyard there was a string of firecrackers. Dad said they were real firecrackers in those days, very loud. "When I was little I was terrified of them. Every time, I would cover my ears and hide far away." He said this with a laugh, but his eyes turned red.\n\nIn the holographic image, a small boy in a red padded jacket came running out — that was five-year-old Dad. He held a stick of candied hawthorn, grinning so wide you could see the gap where a baby tooth had fallen out.\n\nI looked at Dad, then at the little boy in the image. Seventy years had passed, and the child with the candied hawthorn had become the gray-haired middle-aged man beside me. Yet his eyes, moistening at the sight of the old home, were just as real as the five-year-old\'s.\n\nWhen Dad took off the holographic glasses, he was silent for a long time. Then he said: "Thank you, technology, for letting me go home one more time." He paused. "But if only I could taste one more bite of your grandma\'s dumplings."\n\nThat day I understood something: technology can reconstruct images, sounds, and spaces. But certain things — the warmth of a hug, the taste of a bowl of dumplings — are things technology can never replicate. So while the people beside you are still here, hold them more often.'
