          titleEn: 'The Memory Bakery',
          fullTextEn: 'By Cui Lake in Kunming stands a peculiar bakery. From the outside it looks no different from any other, but what it sells is not ordinary bread — it sells "memory bread."\n\nThe concept works like this: neural imprint technology encodes a segment of memory into a special dough. Eat a piece, and you "experience" someone else\'s memory — see the scenery they saw, feel the emotions they felt. Each loaf holds only one memory. Once eaten, it is gone.\n\nI saved two months of pocket money before I could finally afford a piece. The shelves displayed every flavor: chocolate for "First Time Seeing the Ocean," matcha for "Tokyo in Spring," blueberry for "Aurora Night."\n\nI chose a strawberry one. The label read: "Grandmother\'s Kitchen, Winter 2050."\n\nThe moment I bit in, the world changed. I "became" an eight-year-old boy standing in an old-fashioned kitchen. The pot on the stove bubbled and gurgled; the air was thick with the aroma of braised pork. A white-haired old woman was stir-frying at the counter. She turned her head and smiled: "Go wash your hands — dinner is almost ready."\n\nThe sensation was overwhelmingly real. I could feel the kitchen\'s warmth, smell the dishes, even sense the little boy\'s feeling of safety and belonging. This was someone else\'s grandmother, yet she made me think of my own.\n\nThe "memory" lasted only three minutes, then I was back in the bakery. Strawberry sweetness still lingered in my mouth, but my eyes were wet.\n\nWalking out, I found myself thinking: if I could turn my own memories into bread, which would I choose? Perhaps the evening I sat with Grandma in the courtyard watching stars. I hope that years from now, a stranger biting into that loaf will feel the breeze of that night, and the warmth of Grandma\'s palm.\n\nMemories fade. But memories baked into bread might last forever. That, I think, is the reason this bakery exists.'
