          titleEn: 'The Last Tree',
          fullTextEn: 'In the year 2200, only one tree remained on Earth. It was enclosed in a massive glass dome, installed in the central hall of United Nations headquarters.\n\nMy name is Xiaolin. I am twelve years old. I have never seen a real tree — except this one. Every year our school organizes a visit to see it, the way you would visit a dinosaur fossil in a museum. Except this fossil is still alive.\n\nIt is a ginkgo, said to be eight hundred years old. Its leaves are fan-shaped, golden, trembling faintly under artificial sunlight. The guide told us that two hundred years ago Earth still had trillions of trees, but deforestation and climate change erased them one by one.\n\n"If all the trees are gone, where does our oxygen come from?" I asked my teacher.\n\n"Oxygen factories." She gestured at the towering manufacturing columns visible through every city window. They split carbon dioxide into oxygen using electrical energy. The air was clean. But it always felt like something was missing.\n\nStanding before the glass dome, I pressed my palm flat against it. The ginkgo was barely a meter away, but I could not touch it. A golden leaf drifted loose and landed on the ground inside the dome. I stared, transfixed — so that is what a falling leaf looks like: it spins on the way down, like a tiny butterfly.\n\n"I wish I could touch it," I murmured. A guard nearby glanced at me and said nothing.\n\nBack home, I searched "forest" in the holographic library. The screen filled with an endless sweep of green — trees packed shoulder to shoulder, sunlight filtering through gaps between leaves. Birds singing, streams running. The image was so beautiful it made my chest ache.\n\nThat night I dreamed I was standing in a forest. Soft fallen leaves cushioned my feet. Layer upon layer of canopy arched above. Wind blew through and the leaves whispered. I reached out and touched the bark of a tree — rough, cool, real.\n\nI have made my decision. When I grow up, I will become a botanist. I will use genetic technology to make this ginkgo\'s seeds germinate again, to fill the Earth with trees once more. Perhaps one day, people will no longer have to look at trees through glass.'
