          titleEn: 'Time Delivery',
          fullTextEn: 'Ding-dong.\n\nThe smart mailbox by the door lit up. "You have a package from the year 2050. Please sign for delivery."\n\nThe year 2050? That was seventy-four years ago! I rushed to open the mailbox. Inside lay a palm-sized brown paper box with a yellowed label: "Time Express | Sender: Li Xiaoming | Recipient: Li Jiabao | Delayed Delivery: 74 years."\n\nLi Xiaoming was my grandfather\'s name. He had been gone for three years.\n\nMy hands began to tremble. I peeled the box open with the care of someone handling porcelain. Inside: a folded letter and a worn old watch. The handwriting on the letter was neat and graceful —\n\n"Jiabao: Hello. I am your grandfather. You may find it strange that a person you have never met is sending you a package. In 2050, the Time Express company had just opened — it stores parcels in a temporal warehouse and delivers them automatically at the set date. I do not know what you look like, how old you are, or what you are doing, but I know you are my grandchild, and I wanted to prepare a gift before you were born. This watch is the first one I bought when I was twenty. It has run for thirty years. Now it is time to pass it to you. Remember: time moves fast. Do not waste it. With love, your grandfather. Written March 2050."\n\nI turned the watch over. On the back case, a line of small characters was engraved: "Time is the most precious gift."\n\nI fastened the watch to my wrist. It had stopped long ago — the battery was dead. But I could feel its weight: the warmth left behind by someone who never saw me yet loved me all the same.\n\nOutside the window, the sky of 2124 was probably no different from the sky of 2050 — the same blue, the same clouds. Time Express can bridge seventy-four years to deliver a gift, but no technology on Earth can let me say "thank you" to my grandfather.\n\nI looked down at the silent watch. It could no longer tell me the time. But it told me something far more important: some love needs no meeting, needs no waiting — it is simply there.'
