          titleEn: 'The Dream Classroom',
          fullTextEn: 'In the year 2150, schools abolished classrooms. In their place came the "Dream Learning System" — students put on a neural headband, entered a shared dream, and attended class inside it.\n\nMy name is Miaomiao. I am a sixth-grader at a primary school in Dehong Prefecture. Today\'s lesson: "Ancient Poetry — Immersive Experience."\n\nThe headband activated. My body still sat in the study chair at home, but my consciousness had traveled thirteen hundred years to the city of Chang\'an. I stood before the gates of Daming Palace, dressed in Tang Dynasty robes, my thirty-one classmates beside me. Our teacher — or rather, our teacher\'s virtual avatar — pointed to the distant towers and said: "Today we will experience the night Li Bai wrote \'Hard Is the Road.\'"\n\nThe scene shifted. We were inside a wine-house. The table was laden with dishes and goblets — virtual, of course: you could smell the aroma but not eat a bite. A middle-aged man in white robes pushed open the door and walked in. That was the AI-simulated Li Bai. His face was heavy with sorrow. He sat down, raised his cup, then set it back.\n\n"Gold goblets of fine wine, ten thousand coins a cup; jade platters of rare delicacies, worth a fortune each." His voice came deep and thick — not the polished tones of a textbook recording, but laced with an indescribable bitterness.\n\n"Watch his expression, everyone," the teacher said. "A feast of wine and delicacies sits before him, yet he cannot eat. Why? Because the court has cast him aside. His heart is full of anguish. This is the line: \'I stop my cup, lay down my chopsticks, cannot eat.\'"\n\nLi Bai stood, drew the sword at his waist, and gazed out the window in desolation. Then — "Someday I shall cleave the waves with a wind-filled sail and cross the boundless sea!" His voice surged without warning, blazing, his eyes alight.\n\nIn that moment the whole class fell silent. I had truly seen Li Bai\'s transformation from despair to defiance. These were no longer cold words on a page — a living, breathing man was unfolding his life\'s anguish and triumph right before us.\n\nAfter class, I could not snap out of it for a long while. My classmate Xiao Zhang said: "That lesson was too real. I nearly applauded Li Bai."\n\nThe Dream Classroom has replaced blackboard and chalk. But one thing has not changed: what moves the heart will always be the emotion behind the words — never the technology itself.'
